reviewText:
This WWII war story follows the classic storyline of soldiers trapped behind enemy lines. In this movie, it is American soldiers in France who have been taken as POWs and then escape. If you watch war movies, it's a story that's been done many times before. But there's a reason for that: people like it. I think we relate to elements of survival and relying on one another to get through hard times, whether that's war times or otherwise. One thing that makes this story a bit different is that female nurses are included in the stranded group. There is also an interesting sub-plot at a Frenchman's house who is ambivalent to help the group.  It's an independent film, not a big-budget studio film, but it delivers well in the independent genre. There are some gritty moments, some very suspenseful scenes, more than one heartwrenching story arc, and action scenes.

As a nice bonus, there is a 20 minute Behind the Scenes feature on the DVD where you can learn about what went into the making of the movie and what an independent production is like.

The last thing we needed was another low budget, badly scripted and poorly edited war film with re-enactors who can't act for toffee; but we don't always get what we want.

The plot is that it's 1944 and some American soldiers are lost behind enemy lines. One of them has a whoopsie in the trench and his Captain gets injured. This gives the makers the excuse to have some nurses in the mix too - for l'amour as it were. Then they have to get back to their lines etc etc.

Now the acting is actually ok in places so that is a break with the norm. The vehicles are all real but we have a tendency to use American materiel and drape a Swastika over the front to disguise it and fool us all into thinking it really is German. Why camouflage a vehicle then advertise it with a ruddy big red, white and black flag?

The music is a bit too dramatic - especially as there is very little action. The scenes go on far too long; this needed some vigorous editing to be honest. There is no tension and any that does build up soon evaporates in the lack of anything happening. The guns are ok in places but those with a keen eye will see some of our Nazi bods sporting a rather `ahead of its time' AK 47. The uniforms are a bit ropey, there are too many plot holes to bother with and the cover art work is pure fantasy.

I tried to find something positive, and apart from some efforts in the acting department - there is nowt - even the plot is so dire and plain bad it is enough to make one cringe; its isn't even so bad that it is funny. If you want to waste your time you could clean your naval button fluff out instead it will be more rewarding.

Somewhat tried and true themes interspersed with enough "what can possibly happen now" to make it worth passing the time.  I agree with the reviewer who gave it 5 stars and wrote about the humanity in war--the best quality of this movie is seeing that shift back and forth.  Some things made absolutely no sense (widower keeping a very tidy farmhouse with (spoiler alert) chocolates in the bottom of a dresser drawer. The German stereotypes are a bit overplayed, I would have liked to see some novelty there.  Regarding the scenery, well, I doubt they could have filmed on their budget in 12 days in Europe, plus obtained all the permits needed to display Hakenkreuzern, etc. Casting was good--Germans looked "German" (uniforms help) including young boys as you would see late in the war, Panzerfausts, I don't think you would see someone quite as rotund as one of the SS officers....The sound quality was a bit troubling. No subtitles, normally I can understand German in films, what was spoken by the "Gruppenfuehrer" was either a dialect I've never heard, or just poorly recorded.  Medals were a bit "kitchy" but most wouldn't notice.  At the end it was quite obvious that leaving the flag on the front of the "Jeep" would have been a problem (as it was in another fairly low budget film set in the Ardennesoffensive (Battle of the Bulge) that I viewed recently)).
Pvt. Lewis saves the day with his good luck charm--okay, a little Alice in Wonderland there but better than many high-tech and high budget films I've had to see recently.  Discussions of "what is a good soldier" made sense and were a break from the action.

Not sure what all the negative reviews are all about.  Maybe they just don't like stories that show humanity in the face of war.  I enjoyed this immensely.  It was suspenseful, and showed humanity on both sides.  It showed how frail and how strong the human spirit can be.  I like it that the nurses were not left out of the picture.  Women played important parts in the war, and on the home front.  The black and white stills in the beginning were beautifully photographed.  Great movie!

Jesus people- this is an indie film- for anyone making a movie do you know how hard it is to make a movie from an idea to production? Great effort- I have been in this industry for 25 years. It's not a perfect film- and there are so few-, but bravo to the cast, the crew, very well shot, good effects. Interesting film about the human condition in a time of great conflict. To the critics: Make a feature film with your own hands before you judge. I really enjoyed your film to the actors, crew & producers. Bravo, well done. You should be proud.

Don't know what the bad reviews were about.  There were only two things I found that didn't seem quite right.  One was the location.  It should have been in a forest with fir trees, and not pine trees.  The other was the one house that the Germans invaded and took over in 'France'.  It was a house right out of the 60's here in the US.  Other than those two things, the movie was very good.  It kept me watching.  The acting was really good, as was the writing.  One has to remember that during the war, many of the troops didn't always talk and act 'military'.  They were just young boys scared to death, and away from home.  I took one star off simply because of the two location errors.  But those two errors wouldn't stop me from recommending this movie.  I enjoyed it.

How can anyone rated this rushed, b_rated junk as exciting and great is beyond comprehension. Good for comic relief if one is drunk or high.

For starters, you have WW2 American soldiers in Vietnam era uniforms. The coveralls the girls wore weren't of the era either. Even the hairstyles of the nurses were inaccurate with one girl having a Stevie Nicks style do. They end up at a "French" farmhouse that looks exactly like a small country cottage in the architectural style of American South. Clapboard with cute shutters and a nice front porch with wooden columns. Inside complete with a regulator clock, iron bed in the bedroom and country cottage style painted white dresser. And the photo of the mans wife wasn't anything like it should have looked like in that era and was in a cheap walmart frame. The barn was unlike any European barn I've ever seen in my six trips, just a wooden out building, not a typical European stone barn.... also a corrugated tin sided shed complete with a slat back country rocking chair and a country quilt for cover. Not even close. Some of the German uniforms looked authentic in the tunics and headgear. Rifles were M1's and Mauser k98 which were good. Not a great plot or believable story line.  Not to mention it looked like some of the German soldiers had nine lives coming back in later scenes once they had already been killed off....Kind of laughable overall and not worth a watch. I could make a better movie myself....

My husband and I love movies and documentaries about WWII and have seen many. I have got to say this was easily the worst we ever have seen. The acting was amateurish, and the actors' words were out of sync with their moving lips. The movie started out OK but rapidly deteriorated until the ending, which was really bad. The actors manage to escape captivity by setting explosives in broad daylight all around their German prison camp, and their escape vehicle is American and barely altered to look "German." They race out of camp and continue on their way through American lines with a Nazi flag still plastered on the front of their vehicle. It's little wonder that their American compatriots fire on them before they have a chance to explain. By the end of this film we actually were laughing as though it were meant to be a comedy. So, if you decide to watch without taking this film seriously, you may enjoy it.

My tolerance for self flagellation lasted approximately 44 minutes before I had to stop watching. This should give you an idea as to how bad this excuse for a movie truly was. If nothing else, it was inspirational insomuch as I felt inspired to grab my HD camcorder and make my own film in my backyard since even that would be a step up from The Last Rescue. Yes, it really was that bad.

Everything about it was amateurish from the script to the acting. I never criticize a motion picture for a lack of a budget, in fact, I'm more likely to heap extra praise on it whenever it's pulled off. Unfortunately this wasn't the case in The Last Rescue. The setting didn't even remotely resemble the thick green woods of northern France during the Autumn. Instead, it looked more like Northern California during the Summer. While there was an authentic feel to the German uniforms, the American uniforms looked as though they belonged in the hot Pacific Theater rather than the much colder European theater. If details like those don't bother you, then consider yourself free to focus on the script and plot...both of which are riddled with the cheesiest of cliches i.e. the widower (and GQ model) living alone in the woods who takes in the runaway band of POWs. Wouldn't you know it, but it just so happens that among the POWs is a beautiful nurse who just happens to be a widow as well! Cut straight to eye-roll. The more successful directors within the motion picture industry have finally realized that you shouldn't make a German soldiers speak English as the vast majority of them clearly didn't speak English during that time frame. The "Vee have vays of making you talk" era of English speaking German villains has largely come and gone...but not in this throwback piece of cinematic trash. Forget about hiring German speaking actors and the use of subtitles to give an air of realism. Instead, this film doubles down and even includes the evil German laugh after this iconic line "Don't vorry madam, vee vill be out of your vay in no time so long as you aren't hiding anyone...like a jew (insert evil laugh here). I could go on and on but there isn't enough space on the internet. In fact, please don't consider this a review but rather more of a public service announcement.

Well, I guess with so much reenacting stuff around and reenacting groups, when you get bored you make a movie.  A pathetic movie.  This thing is supposed to be set in August 1944 in NE France when the 101st and 82nd Airborne divisions were back in the UK waiting for their next drop which didn't happen until the middle of September; nevertheless, there they were, "soldiers" from both divisions in the middle of this thing.  I restored a 1945 MB jeep and a 1942 Dodge WC51 so I know a little about the military vehicle collectors. It's always nice to see the old hardware - even in this case an M36 TD.  But geez, guys - the round loaded in the M36 90 mm looked like it had just been dug up.  Same for the rifle ammunition.  And how come so much shooting and obviously empty ammo pouches.  Nice try, but get a life................and know some history.  Don't quit your day jobs.

The uniforms are very good reproductions (there are a number of suppliers available today to the general public and re-enactors), the blank adapters on the ends of the M1's were too noticeable (they could have used the shorter ones available) and the hair on the men was too long to be even remotely according to regulations during combat.  The German Army historically did use captured US equipment, but this movie has the German's using so much American vehicles you would think the US Army Quartermaster Corps was their main source of equipment!  Additionally, the acting was very poor, the dialog was as though they were reading it off a prompter and the movie's scenario was too far fetched to be considered credible by any stretch of the imagination..

This is one of the first amazon reviews I've ever written. I was compelled to do so by how HORRIBLE this movie was. I almost turned it off with 10 minutes to go, I cared so little about how it would end. The acting is horrendous and the characters - especially American - look like and speak like they are set in modern times. With such a huge collection of WWII movies setting the genre, there is no excuse for such anachronistic writing. The plot is just boring - I don't care at all about the characters as there is no character development, just a bunch of stereotypes (the tough yet respected leader, the scared kid, the fearless tough guy, the strong woman, the weak woman, the a-hole German, the sympathetic German...).

Hanging Swastika flags on American Jeeps and driving around France. Shooting prisoners one minute then talking to them and wasting time trying to find one of them and doing nothing else. Frustrating portraits of weak people who would never  make it though basic training. The is a real pile.

I wanted to see how Cody Kasch would do in a role so different from the one he played in Desperate Housewives, and to be honest, I love Gilles Marini and Johann Urb. I gave the movie 5 stars because as an indie film it totally satisfied my expectations.
